<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1947-02-11T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1947-02-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="397" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d397">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">Marshall Mission Files, Lot 54–D270:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Colonel <persName type="from">George V.
                                    Underwood</persName> to Lieutenant General <persName type="to">Alvan C. Gillem, Jr.</persName>, at Peiping</hi><note n="21" xml:id="d397fn21">Repeated to Colonel Carter in Washington.</note>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1947-02-11">11 February
                                1947</date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>2067. This message is sent at the request of Doctor Stuart.</p>
                        <p>The Generalissimo asked Doctor Stuart to inform you that he earnestly
                            hoped the inactivation of Executive Headquarters would not remove you
                            from the China scene. He expressed admiration for <pb facs="0725" n="715" xml:id="pg_715"/> you personally and genuine appreciation
                            for your past efforts and assistance.</p>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>